Espresso;-;Review for Civilization V with Gods and Kings/Brave New World, November 2013: Civilization V may have gotten off to a rocky start. The streamlined interface, and the removal of staples such as unit stacking were a bit of a shock, and the feeling was different. With patching and updates, however, Civilization V has grown into its own game that stands apart from its predecessors. I won't say it's better than previous games. I won't say the historic immersion is the same (although Brave New World goes a long way to making that come back). So unfortunately, coming into Civ V after playing a previous Civ game will feel awkward and possibly unsatisfying, but this is a game that rewards you with the time you put into it, it gets better as you play it. What remains missing however, is the diplomacy. The expansions have done a lot to repair the broken diplomacy system, and it works much better than before, but there remains a lack of choices for the player. Many systems from previous games, such as spying, tech stealing, and religion, have been restored magnificently to the game in the expansions, but remain missing from the base version. With Brave New World, a lot of the community feels that the game is now on par with the previous game, Civilization IV: Beyond The Sword. I'm not sure I agree, but it certainly is a close call. Civilization V is far less tedious than Civ IV, but still not as immersive. Most of the complaints about Civilization V come from older players, familiar with older Civ games, but Civilization V is a great starting point for the series and strategy games in general. Compared to similar games like Europa Universalis, or even Civilization IV, Civilization V is very easy to learn and has an intuitive interface and adjustable difficulty. Even on higher difficulty, the game features unobtrusive advice which you can choose to follow. No matter if you're a newcomer or a Civ-veteran, Civ V still has the infamous "One more turn" addictiveness this series is known for. And overall, this is my favorite game on Steam currently, and I often have recommended it to people. It's an all-around great game. ----- Original recommendation, June 2012: This is not the most satisfying Civilization game. It may be one of the most fun, however. The classic game is still there, streamlined and reengineered so that less time is spent micromanaging, and more time is spent planning your conquest of the world. The graphics are the best of any Civ game so far, and there are many gameplay surprises that keep you replaying and trying out new things. It is becoming one of my all-time favorites.
