Lord Sipia;-;You there! Are you able to steer every part of a budding nation to greatness? Do you want to squabble with other nations over resources like bananas and uranium? Are you able to deal with Montezuma declaring war with you every fifteen turns or so? Can you stop that scheming  Gandhi from nuking you to extinction? If you answered "Yes" to all, or at least most of these questions, then you should try out Civilization V. You won't be disappointed. I haven't played the other Civilization games, so I'm not sure how they compete, but this game is certainly friendly to newcomers to the series. The game is very intuitive and helps you keep the game moving by pointing out what you still need to do this turn before letting you move on to the next- no more checking every unit and every city six times like in the Total War games! The game offers several options for victory- you can simply kill 'em all, you can send a spaceship to Alpha Centauri to prove your technological dominance, you can make your civilisation the cultural center of the world, or you can win through diplomacy by earning votes in the United Nations (that is, as soon as you build it! Yes, YOU!). There's several ways in which your civilization has to compete with their rivals- there's luxury resources scattered across the map which are vital in keeping your empire happy, there's strategic resources which are required to build certain units and buildings (factories require coal, for instance), there's city states which will favor the most helpful (or most generous) civilization and grant them the earlier-mentioned resources, and of course, there's the everlasting race to keep your economy and military up to par with the other players. Each player is outfitted with a unique AI, but you can also choose to randomize them to keep the game unpredictable. All in all, this game offers more strategies than countable. What do you research first? Where do you send your new citizen to work? Where are you going to settle your new city? How many cities do you need for your plan for world domination, anyway? Will you build a wall to defend yourself or a library to speed up your research? And so on. TL;DR version: Plenty of tactics to be found here. If you like turn-based strategy games, this one's for you.
