mrkmkz;-;Civilization 5 has had an interesting journey over the years and remains the game I have most likely wasted the most time on. But do not think it is perfect in any ways, it is as flawed as a game can be. I will not waste time on Single Player as the AI is either unfair on Diety and it is a challenge so far that you have to play one exact way to win or ly stupid and all you do is haul those wonders and wait for a time to attack. Their attack strategies are mediocre at best and even with number advantage you are able to defeat the opponent without any issues. But there is a reason I only played Civ Beyond Earth 30 hours and this game since then 500 hours. And it is the Multiplayer. Back in the day I used to play Civ 3 with some buddies on Hot Seat Mode and that was a blast, so going into Civ 5 I started playing MP right away and have not been disappointed, well I have been but more on that later. The team games are awesome, they require great tactics and strategy and are highly competitive given you play with the right group. FFAs are plenty and can be fun too, there is nothing more rewarding than winning a 6 hour game. At the beginning there are several ways to be competitive and one has to make quick and rash decisions on whether to build wonders, cities or units. There is a default way to be effective but one still has to analyse its territory. With the addons this just becomes better as one has to decide whether to go for that early pantheon, how to deal with city states and potential neighbors. Sometimes an early rush is the only option you have to succeed. This is what makes the game great, you are required to make game altering decisions quickly and early. It is not like AoE where you can play with a preset mindset as sometimes it just dont work out. When you are playing as Babylon, a science powerhouse, but you see yourself surrounded by 2 players, your typcial play by rushing Great Library will not be possible anymore. With all the updates and addons I do have to say I like the current setup of Wonders as well as the selection of Natural Wonders. There are some which are gamebreaking and are usually banned, e.g. Great Wall. But I do like them as a adjustment to your game. The Natural Wonders are IMO also quite nicely balanced, except of course El Dorado and the Fountain of Youth, which are rare spawns. The 500 Gold equalizes an early Settler buy or 2 workers, which gives you a great advantage to do anything. Fountain of Youth gives you 10 happiness plus higher Reg, you can expand without worries for a long time. But it is possible to still defeat a person with these wonders, something that can be rewarding. The Tech Tree I always had my issues with as it is pretty locked and sometimes offers little room for strategy. There are some techs which are game deciding, Crossbows and Navigation the most apparent ones. Later one as the tech tree branches out one has to make a decision on getting certain techs while neglecting others. One of the toughest decisions is always on whether getting Public Schools or Artillery, Science or the 3 range unit. Early on I always play a default setup, I rarely adjust it to the start. C
