drewthegreat;-;Well for one, it's actually called Civilization V instead of a "rehash" (I'm looking at you Sim City and DmC) so for that it gets props. This review is under the assumption you know what the CIvilization series is. Let me acknowledge right off the bat the comparisons to Civ 4 are justified, but don't let that you bypass this game altogether. Pros: Nice graphics - compared to the previous entries, it sure is a breath of fresh air, rendered clouds, and detailed terrian, fluid ocean live, and units. Soundtrack - high quality tracks that reflect whatever nation you choose to play, but can get old if you play for an extended period, have background music streaming when you tire of it Gameplay - Hex tiles deserve to be mentioned as they promote better tactics with adjacent units. Various options to select from including victory types, barbarian spawns, turn limits, world fertility, and map types Replayability - very high considering the nation DLC releases, Gods and Kings expansion which adds religion and esponiage that grant passive national bonuses and perks, Various tech and research upgrades tailored to your particular strategy, whether domination, culture, and science Mods - works very well with the Steam workshop and increases replayability. Recommended mods: R.E.D. Modpack, InfoAddict, and Real Earth Map Cons: Multiplayer - It is enjoyable to play against or with friends, but you can only play online without mods of any kind (this includes statistical mods like InfoAddict) AI - The major thing lacking for me personally, I can get lucky and spawn on an island and defend it quite easily using a few trained water tile ships. Nation leaders tend to be sporadic (even with their personalities mirrored to history) and childish at times. Trade agreements can be outrageously disproportionate to the demands being made. Great Turn based strategy game that fulfills what it was created to do.
