Ayuri;-;Civilization V is probably one of the most complete, detailed and fascinating strategy game I've ever played. I highly recommend it.
A. Yeager;-;This is a game that is very complex to master, but it's easy to learn the concept. I usually have a hard time grasping games like these due to a learning difficulty, but this game has a very good tutorial system as well as advisors that points out to you what needs to be done around your lands to improve it. What I like Culture divirsity The game becomes very beautiful to watch thanks to the leaders bringing their own culture to the game. The character models are very well detailed and features clothing that is appropriate for their time. There's also a fantastic soundtrack which will play music depending on who you are playing with. My favorites include the music while playing Morocco as well as the beautiful "I wow to thee my country" while playing with Elizabeth of England. Leader personalities Each leader behaves a certain way and when you have the game randomized, it gives a big diversity to the playstyle. Some leaders will go for a cultural victory and will mostly be pleasent to those around to be able to cross their borders. Other leaders are extremely aggressive for a domination victory, so you need to build up your own army early on in case they plan to attack you. You can't be friends with everyone Your neighbors will make you mad and you will get mad with them. I have tried so many times to be pleasent to everyone, but after a while there will be disagreements. Border tensions when you want the land your neighbor owns, differences on science or cultural approach, religion views. Some neighbors deliberately try to force themselves on your lands by building cities where your borders expand and the only way to deal with that is going to war. Different approaches to victory You don't have to take over the world if that isn't your style, you could boost your science or culture to win over the opponents. You can also turn off some of the winning conditions if they don't suit you. In my case, I think the time victory is boring, because it happens too soon. Or if taking over the world is your style, you could turn off all the other victory conditions and force the opponents to fight you. Good game options Find barbarians annoying? Turn them off. Don't like the spy system? Turn it off. There are many good options to tailor the way you prefer to play. You decide what to do You're not forced into anything. You could put your focus on military, expanding your lands, upping your culture... basically, it is up to you. Some games I have not focused on winning overall, but getting revenge on an opponent that has been a thorn in the side. What I dislike Others leaders usually have resource advantage There's no way to know where some resources exist until very late in the game. It's very frustrating to have played 300 turns and then realize all your neighbors have access to uranium, but you don't, because that resource was placed near all their starting cities. It allows them to use nuclear weapon on you, but you can't use it on them unless you can convince them to trade it with you. Which leads me to... Other leaders are cheapskates Whenever the other leaders make trade offers with you, they offer 1 gold for a rare resource they don't have. When you want a rare resource from them, they expect you to give all your other luxury resources. What gives? Sometimes you can trade luxury for luxury, but they will always try to offer you a bad deal if they can. I do wish there had been a game option which would let you refuse an offer forever until set to accept it again. I do not want Attila to have an embassy in my city, because I know the first thing he'll do is attack me with his army. That doesn't stop him from asking fifty times.
