The ZooZ;-;For those who like the genre, it is a step-up on the previous installments regarding (obviously) additional options, especially with the 2 expansions, Gods and Kings and Brave New World. The social policies changes and the introduction of religion options and city-states and interaction with said city-states, were the biggest changes in the game in terms of different things to do. That said, i think there's still room for improvement on additional options you might have in terms of policy choosing, etc. The economy system is also a bit different from previous installments, a bit richer, and i think the military aspect of the game improved a lot in terms of tactics. Granted, still room for improvement there, but much less 'cheesy' tactics like stacking 20 units in a tile, for instance. You now really need to know where to position your units, and use choke points, etc. to your advantage. Much more 'chess-like' than 'win-by-more-numbers'. Some of the different win conditions have also gained more depth, especially the diplomatic / cultural victory. The mods from the steam workshop are also insanely rich, giving you even more customization / replay value to the game. Lastly, the graphics have obviously also improved a lot, with a lot more detail, even though, at least for me, that's the least concerning aspect of a game such as this. Its downsides (as usual) mostly revolve around the need to have a sufficiently good pc to handle the burden of loading times, etc., as it is quite heavy on your pc. Most games also tend to have a mid-game era which is quite stale, where pretty much nothing happens regardless of whether you're far ahead, far behind or even with the majority of the other civs. AI is also something that still hasn't improved as much as i would have liked. It is either too aggressive or too passive, but not really playing intelligently, regardless of difficulty level, but rather as usual, gaining more bonuses to make up fo the lack of actual Intelligence on the Artificial Intelligence part. So, breaking it down: Pros: - Even more tech / social options, richer interaction with city-states; - Religion now plays a big role in the game; - More depth in cultural / diplomatic win conditions; - Improved combat / tactical aspect of the game; - Improved mod / customization in steam workshop; - Lots of replay value; - Better graphics. Cons: - Game can be quite the resource-hog on your pc, regardless of having or not a good one. - Some games can turn out to be stale for quite some time, depending on specific spawn points, etc. - Could still have improved social policy choosing, despite the huge improvements on that aspect. - AI's actual intelligence part hasn't really improved, in my opinion. TL;DR: A solid 8.5 out of 10, whether you're new to the franchise, or have played them all since the very first pixelated Civilization 1, like myself. Would honestly give it more, if the loading times were faster. I don't mind putting in the hours playing the game, it's just a bit bothersome knowing that a somewhat significant part of those hours are spent waiting, rather than playing.
