omgggg clarissa;-;This turn-based strategy game is reasonably deep and very fun and has tons of value behind it. As far as strategy games go, this one is definitely one of the most accessible. Learning how to play is easy and rewarding. The Brave New World expansion is a must-have as it adds plenty of gameplay elemetns that truly enhance the game altogether. A couple minor gripes: The AI is too easy, and on higher difficulties they are only given advantages like money or science boosts rather than actually playing the game more intelligently and strategically. This is pretty unfair. Essentially they are just given cheats compared to you. Tons of fun if you have eight hours to play a game with friends in a LAN setting (don't let those conniving s peek at your screen though). Anyone who loves this game would do themselves a service to check out Civilization 4 which is actually more in-depth than Civ 5 in many regards, because in making Civ 5 more accessible it was dumbed down a bit.
[INACTIVE til 08/24] Payne Train;-;If you travelled back in time a few years and told my past self I'd be interested in this game, I'd probably think you were crazy. I'm not one particularly fond of strategy games such as Civ, but this game has given me many hours of an enjoyable democratic and peaceful bloodthirsty and back-stabbing game. The base game, Civ V, on its own is enjoyable. Although, what really gives the game some "flavour" are the two DLC packs released. Altogether these create an enjoyable gaming experience. The gameplay and strategy is a "easy to learn, hard to master" style that in as little as a few hours you'll be chopping Ghandi's armies to your left and developing Nuclear Fission to your right. In multiplayer, this game is Monopoly with friends on crack. You'll find yourself making alliances and checking your backs every turn until the game is over. You may lose a few friends in the process, but hey, all is fair in love and war. Definitely recommend getting the entire game + DLC.
