Rajah Bimmy;-;Gameplay (5/5): Builds stress at all the right times, and certain AI add extra flavor Graphics (4/5): Takes a bit of time and tinkering to run smoothly, and your computer definitely will get a little toasty, but this is made up for by the stunning amount of resources the game can handle at once. Design (5/5): The devil is in the details, and Civ is packed with bells and whistles on every tile. The UI can appear daunting at first but in the long run becomes incredibly simplistic. Sound (4/5): The score and narration really enhance the immersion and make your civilization's story all the more epic. Multiplayer (3/5): The only aspect of the game that is just average. The graphics and amount of AI the game can handle take a significant blow in multiplayer, and the way the game freezes entirely if you're at war with another player and it's their turn can be frustrating. The lack of achievement support in multiplayer is also a bit disappointing. PC Factor (5/5): The mod support is absolutely fantastic and propels this game to be a staple of PC gaming. Replay Factor/Achievements (5/5): By the end of one really long game, you will have a full understanding of how to play and be ready to rack up another hundred hours over the course of two days (this game will make you think that's possible) Civilization V is the kind of game that may lead you to rehab, but that'll only hurt your loved ones and you're two turns away from learning how to build a giant atomic robot so who cares? Overall: 8.9
