JussiMuussi | 2/2015 KARPR;-;Civilization is a game that really takes time to learn. It's easy to learn the basics, especially if you have played other strategy games before, but the actual learning begins after that. Turn by turn, everything that you do in the beginning and after that, affects the endgame, so you will have to know right at the beginning what to research or build and so on. And it's not like every game is based on same decisions, because the game is constantly changing and there are multiple ways to achieve victory. Usually, if you play at [/b]normal[/b] speed, the games take >10h to play, so I wouldn't recommend this game to those who like fast-paced action duh . Civ V is a great way to waste your weekends playing games and not doing anything useful, so if you like long term strategy games with plenty of challenge, I think that this is your game. P.S. I would recommend you buy the Gods and Kings & Brave New World (especially the BNW), because those bring new elements to the game, and BNW changes the game dramatically.
XB92AI;-;In my opinion, this is one of the best strategy games around. The base game is pretty bland, however the two expansion packs are what make Civilization V as good as it is. The expansions add new civilizations and great game mechanics like trade routes via boats and caravans, tourism, religion. These can all Impact the game in such a fantastic way and add a little more complexity to the gameplay. I believe that Civ V i best played with friends. We love to pick random Civilization's and set the AI to random personalities. This makes the game pretty muchh different every time we play it. Gandhi may not be a  this time around, Washington might not just continue to expand all over your borders. It is good fun, especially when co-operating with one another about trading, swapping resources and even war. If you have the slightest interest in Strategy games, this is for you. I do recommend both expansion packs, though.
