Stylether;-;I highly recommend Civ to anyone who likes to build their own history a little. It's a game that shines when you invest yourself in it and explore the possibilities. As any avid civ player can tell you, you will truly form a symbiotic (or perhaps parasitic) relationship with your fellow players and AI, all the while it being virtual and fictional, and feel like history is really progressing inside your little realm. As every player schemes their way forward, that one settler takeover 200 turns earlier might be the reason why you decided to decimate someone's Civ. Or at the very least embargo them. Do you expand rapidly, or keep it calm and small? Do you initiate combat with your neighbours, or leave them as a safezone for potential invaders at the other end. Puppets and city razing, science and faith, everything is a factor in your ultimate victory... or very untimely demise. In short, if you don't mind sinking hours into a virtual world and rant in frustration as your neighbour finishes your favorite wonder first, a good casus beli for war if I've ever heard one, then you shouldn't really be searching for anything else, because you found exactly what you'd want just a buttonpress away. And probably a lot of cash.
