Cracktus Jack;-;Sid Meiers Civilization V Complete is a turned-based 4x strategy game. From the stone age to the space age, lead your civilization to span the globe, competing against your rivals as you establish cities, research technologies and build your units to stand the test of time. This review is based on the base game, the Gods & Kings and Brave New World expansions, and 13 DLCs that add additional Civilizations, map generators and game scenarios. Pros : Bringing the game to hexagons and limiting it to 1 unit per tile, are two bold steps away from past versions that completely revolutionized the strategy section of the game, as you must now plan, prepare and place your units. You have a huge selection of distinct civilizations to chose from, each of their leaders being memorable opponents, may they be friend or foe depending of which religion they adopt in the early game, or which social ideology they identify to in the late game. Will you use brute force to have your armies march through your enemies, overrun other cultures with yours with the tourism generated by your arists, writers, musicians or artifacts from archeological digs, use trade routes and influence to have other nations and city states to elect you World Leader of the united nations, or surpass humanitys science as you send the first interstallar ship to Alpha Centauri? Cons : There is little in form of story, quests or accomplishments to be had in a game. The AI negociation, although better than past Civilizations, is still broken when it comes to negociating or reasonning with it. The game itself is a resource hog, and the game will slow down in late game no manner how powerful your PC or Mac is. Verdict : I strongly recommand this game! The replayability is incredible, you can play a thousand game and never play the same one twice. The variety of civilizations allow you to try different approach, different styles and different strengths with each play through.
