Cardinal_UK;-;Out of all my steam games, this is the one game I keep coming back to. When it was first released, I truly hated it. It was a rushed and broken game. Now, it has become one of my all-time favourite games. The turn based nature of this game means you get the time to plan your empire and diplomatic strategy. Battles can become large chess-like conflicts that require you to look at the bigger picture - simple numbers will not win you a fight (unless on the easiest difficulty of course). The game is engaging with a gigantic tech tree to keep you interested. There are also numerous scenarios to choose from, such as the fall of Rome and the American Civil War. You can also fully customise your game and create your own scenarios for you and your friends to play. The vanilla game is massive, and will keep you occupied for many an hour trying to crush, bribe, sleaze or geek your way to victory. Then there is the added bonus of the workshop turning this already huge game into an endless, life sucking monster from which there is no return. In all, I love this game and if you like Turn Based Strategy games this is definitely one you need in your collection.
Lord Kryos;-;JUST... ONE... MORE... TUUUUUUUUURN
Pookie;-;Ooh, are you thinking about buying this game? I love it, and the reason I love it? Because I can PLAY it. I'm not one for impossible games that you have to do again and again and again and you still die before the checkpoint - you can set the difficulty on this, and the difficulties seem to be pretty wide ranging. Very accessible to newer players, but with progression for those people out there who are just amazing at whatever game they touch! About playing it, though - you have to have the time to devote to it. Those with families or busy social lives will probably start resenting their families or friends because they want to be playing, and those without will never have a reason to stop! You just set yourself targets of, "once I've got to there, I'll stop", but by that time, you're working on something else! "Just. One. More. Turn." And that's just the first game - there's so many variations because there's so much choice of progression throughout the game, and then there's all those trophies (I do love a good trophy collection), that even when you finish the first game, you're already plotting which leader and which strategy you'll be next! I really enjoy the expansion Brave New World - I'm glad they brought religion back, culture victories are much more interesting, and trade routes are a good way to boost income (and partially equalise the science of nations). And if half the words I'm saying make no sense - don't worry; a lot of the game can be automated, the advisors don't steer you too far wrong, and if you've put it on easy enough, you're army will overpower the others soon enough to give you a satisfying first, albeit violent, victory.
