SultanK;-;Author background Welcome to my first ever review. Have fun reading, and hoping this review can inform and/or enrich you in any way. A short introduction of myself, and then let's start reviewing. I'm a 35 year old, male Civilization-veteran, who has been playing the Civ-franchise since the release of the first Civilization. Married, have two adorable, young sons, onto hopefully my knowledge and enthousiasm might spread. Residing in Belgium, Europe. Important changes towards previous versions The biggest and one of the best changes, in my opinion, are the new hexagonal tiles versus the old square tiles. This concept isn't new and was already being used in other, older strategy/history games/sims. It makes you wonder why it took until Civ5 before using these. Now it feels right when moving units around the map. In older versions of Civ it always felt like a bit of cheating to move a unit diagonally from one square tile to another. Suppose you could not move diagonally, you would need double the movement points to move around squares forming a corner. Now while you can move diagonally, you gain a distinct distance advantage while doing so, 1,4 distance against 1 while moving straight. (diagonal=sqrt(2*length)) (1,414=sqrt(2*1)). In a hexagonal system, movement in all 6 directions measure the same distance. Size does matter! The most pleasant change for me, was the new combat system related to distance units. Just how cool was it to let it rain arrows (and havoc) upon your foes with that newly build archery unit? Besieging cities is much more fun now than it used to be. The fact that hills and/or mountains block range, doesn't only add a bit of unit realism, but is definitely a very important strategic implement. Because of units can't form stacks on tiles anymore, they should be looked at as individual armies. Combine this with the reduced number of tiles (max 6 instead of max 8) coming from the new hex grid, directly surrounding a city, you really have to think twice when positioning units to launch a coordinated city assault. Also bearing in mind, the possibility for units to retreat to safe distance for healing. These changes grant so much more strategic depth than in Civ5's predecessors. In fact, Civ5 is the first version I'm perfectly happy with when it comes to strategy. Like with any other older version of the game, it all looks a bit better. From the maps, cities, units, unit animations, menu's, etc. Everything is visually improved. Content Vanilla version comes with 18 civilizations, with 7 civs available in DLC, and respectively 9 and 9 more with the expansions Gods & Kings and Brave New World. Making a total of 43 civilizations to beat the game with! Each of the civs having their unique leader together with his/her personal traits, and unique units/buildings. Map sizes range from duel (very small) to huge. Not having checked this thoroughly, my guess is that the huge map is much larger than the greatest size in Civ4. And by huge, I do mean HUGE. Steam Hooray, Civilization 5 is affiliated with Steam! This brings the community closer to the gamer. It's a great resource for (free) downloadable mods and guides, discussion forums, etc... Basically all the advantages Steam gives to a gamer can be enjoyed now as well in your favorite strategy game Civ 5 should be. Personally, I just adore the Steam achievements. A welcome addition in a game that can be played over and over again with randomly generated maps. Over time I found it rather hard to keep playing when I've beaten (and lost) the game so often, that no real/ultimate goal remained. Steam achievements solved this motivation problem for me. I also concluded my gaming-style improved due to the variation of games I had to play to unlock achievements. My ultimate goal is to unlock all 287 of them, and be rewarded a perfect game. Hope to do this before Civ 6 is released. At the time I'm writing this review I got 96 unlocked with 203 hours played. Downsides Yes, in a game so developed and grown over even a decade, there are some downsides I have to mention. First of all the AI. You can begin to notice repetitive, predictable AI behavior having played for, let's say over 150 hours. This is not new in comparison to older versions, and I understand this is something that can remain an issue over a longer period of time in the future from now. A computer remains a programmed machine, right?! This may not be a problem to online gamers who play against other humans, but I play Civ against AI for 99% of the time. Also, when playing on higher difficulty levels, the benefits the computer controlled civs get, become too prominent and annoying. Frustrated me especially on the two highest difficulty levels, Immortal and Deity. I recommend King and Emperor levels for experienced players, maybe Immortal on smaller and/or duel-sized maps. Deity simply is too insane to spent (too) much time on. Another minor downside may be the fact Firaxis removed religion from the game, in the vanilla version that is. With the installment of Gods & Kings, religion can be brought back. Although it is implemented differently like it was in Civ4, I must add. Some civ-specific units might be over/underpowered towards other civ-specific units. All in all, if this is all downside I can think of, Firaxis created another great title. Conclusion A truly must-have for every fan of the Civilization franchise, a great recommendation for everyone who loves turn-based strategy games. With the game being released for years now, the Civilization 5 complete pack (all DLC, expansions Gods & Kings and Brave New World) is regularly on sale and can be purchased for less than 15 (USD 12). Having bought the complete pack myself for 13, it's the best 13 ever spent so far! Buy this ASAP and start growing civilized even more! Greetings Have fun!
