BlackEagle;-;Civilization 5 often passes off as a slight downgrade from other civ games. Many of it's initial concepts can steer away previous civ fans who enjoyed features that are now simplified, but what they don't realise is how much more this game offers to make up for it. The hexagon system of tiles is one of the greatest ideas they've ever had - no longer is it more efficient to move diagonally than it is in any other direction, as with hexagons no direction is any more efficient than another. The worlds have grown in size to an astonishing amount when maxed out, and the units now feel much more like true squads or platoons rather than board game pieces with their large visual numbers and more advanced battle animations, not to mention vastly improved graphics. Units also can no longer be stacked on top of one another - each tile is limited to only 1 military and 1 civilian (settler/worker/great person), meaning you can't stack entire armies ready to march on the enemy's capital with certain destruction in a matter of only 1 turn as you could in previous titles. Overall, everything this game does feels so much better than the previous games in the series. They did a fantastic job polishing it to the point of once again holding it's point as the greatest strategy game ever.
