Nefara;-;The only valid reason for any strategy game lover to not have and love this game is the fear for your life. And by that, I don't mean dying, I just mean having it tick away via seconds and minutes and inevitably hours sunk into this game. It's addicting. But luckily, it's a sort of benign addiction in that after you finally *do* wipe the smile from Ramallamadingdong's face and crush the Siamese army with battleships and B2's you can look upon a world uniformly flying your colors and feel satisfied. It might lack some of the finer points of control and systems that games like Europa Universalis or a couple of previous iterations of Civ had, but I feel it was a fair trade for how approachable it is. Civ 5 is extremely easy to learn, but difficult to master. Even after as many hours as I've sunk into it, I'm still learning new strategies and how to deal with challenges and there's no lack of depth here. In vanilla civ 5, yes, but with the expansions? No. It's a great strategy game to dive into that's unintimidating for the newbies and deep enough for the hardcore.
