[Merc] Boylaska;-;Pro: -great turn-based strategy timeline evolution -very easy to learn -endless replayability -awesome singleplayer -good graphics for its genre -calming soundtrack -many different game setups -fun city management -lots to build, upgrade and research! -game gives suggestions on what to build, upgrade or research -decent diplomaticy system -action -> reaction, for example: expand your territory near other civilizations -> they might get angry -> they might denounce you -> other civilizations might distrust you -> every civilization turns against you -> nukes -> new game -Steam Workshop Con: -Diplomacy system is not perfect, for example: when demanding another civilization to stop spying on you, most of the time (or atleast when they dislike you) they tell you that they're trying to steal research to keep their people safe from you. Whatever the outcome of that conversation, about 1 turn later that civilization contacts you again to tell you that they are sorry. You can then tell them that you forgive them or not. But whatever you choose, they will always try to spy on you again later on. Even if you have a much bigger army than them, it seems that they don't care about risking a war announcement from your side. -Loading time of starting/loading a game takes a bit too long. Verdict: Even though I expected more from the diplomacy system, this is still the best and easiest to learn turn-based strategy game I have ever played. Dlc are a must have to enjoy it to the fullest! Keeps you hooked for many many hours. 9/10! What to buy: I highly recommend getting the full game package! The dlc are a MUST for the full experience, even with Workshop possibilities. P.S. Most players find Civ 5 a better game than the latest Civ: Beyond Earth. I feel the same way about this. Beyond Earth is far from a bad game but it just doesn't keep me hooked the way Civ 5 does. The fact that Civ 5 can be played with all it's DLC, and that Beyond Earth has no big DLC out yet, probably plays a big part in it (overal, BE feels incomplete). Civ 5 has also aged very well. It doesn't look dated at all compared to the latest installment.
