Ben;-;Civ 5 took a while to grow on me. on its first release, I was not impressed. the expansion packs have really added a lot, though, and I think with time I also got over the differences as compared to Civ 4. I'm really torn on the game-iness of Civ 5, though. like I still feel like the social policy trees and the city-states don't naturally fit. they're fun, because you're "leveling up" and "questing", but the policy system of Civ 4 seemed like it made more sense from a simulation point of view and gave you some cool flexibility when your needs changed, and the city state quests quickly become stupid, and again feel more like gimmicky game elements rather than a part of history. but again, the policies are rewarding, and the revamped cultural victory introduced in Brave New World moves them from "gimmicks supporting a weird win condition" to "fun ways to customize your game". I could still do without the city states, though. I agree that the diplomatic victory from previous games was poorly done, and I appreciate that city states do fix this, but it seems like a poorer fix than might have been hoped. on a side-note: I'd be curious to play vanilla Civ 5 and see if it still feels weak compared to vanilla Civ 4, or if my resistance to Civ 5 really WAS just "eew, hexes and non-stacked units - weird!" either way, I have since come to really enjoy Civ 5, especially with Brave New World. I look forward to Civ 6, whatever shape it may take. (unless it's online only. thank god Civ isn't owned by EA.)
