Special Fried Rice;-;Civilization V Is not as 'advanced' as titles such as Europa Universalis and such. what it is , though, is perhaps the most accesible 'grand' strategy' games on the market.it has tutorials that will ease you into the game quickly, and it manages to be understandable and extremely fun for even people new to the series. the game allows you to play the game how you want- you can make a game short or long depending on the amount of time you want to sink in. and you'll want to sink in. even though i said it is 'dumbed down' compared to paradox interactive titles, there is still a hell of a lot to do , not even counting the two massive expansions, although i think the game does feel less engaging without the expansions, so i'd highly recommend getting them. The inclusion of the steam workshop is a nice touch , but not especially new since civ games since 2 , have always had the option of user created content. when you dive into the game , after picking a map , a civ (43 with all dlc) , and a speed, (there are also advanced options which allow you to tweak game settings and spice up the experience, like a one-city challenge) you'll experience the building of your empire from 4000BC To the future, you'll declare war on other civs, or you might engage in trading , or maybe you'll enact a research agreement so you can unlock rifling (Or whatever else). with the two expansions added, a whole new element of diversity is added as you spread religion and tourism, spy on your enemies (and friends) , ultilitize trade caravans, vote on world issues and advancements in the world congress , and pick your civilization's ideology . each expansion gameplay system grants benefits to the player and deeply increases the fun of the early and middle-late game periods. city states(small civs in short) are included in vanilla and expanded upon in the expansions, which allow you to use them for your economic, militaristic or cultural benefit. honestly , there is so much to do , i could go on for days. do note that the ai and diplomacy is severely better in the expansions, so i would defintely recommend them too. multiplayer is apparently good too , although i haven't played much of that. Civ 5 is hard to sum up in one word. i could write ten articles , but i'll have to settle with 'fantastic'.
