The Corsican;-;A great game that combines strategy and history to form one of the most exciting games I have experienced. The replay value is very high, as you will never get the same experience out of Sid Meier's Civilization V twice. Whether you're playing a solo game, or a Domination match against a handful of friends, you will not regret purchasing this game! That being said, I feel obligated to give a small disclaimer: Even if you devote your life and soul to this strategic masterpiece, you will not always win. Especially in multiplayer. You will have times where barbarians are relentlessly attacking your capital until your scientific utopia turns into Detroit with legalized meth. You will have times where you decide to pick a new civ, and realize that the civ you chose is utterly repugnant. You will have times where you are trying your hardest to keep your citizens from starving, rebelling, being unhappy, being enslaved/captured, up until some warmongering brickhouse beats the living daylight out of you and you watch as everything you have spent the last three days building gets completely #rekt. I have now around 250 hours on Civilization V, and to this day I have never won a multiplayer match against my friends (they're much better than I am at this game lol), and Ghandi still nukes my cities while I flee in terror. But I love the feeling of having an army at my command, having multiple options to win a game, having the choice to form alliances or betrayals, and watching your village grow into a oversized metropolis with giant death robots and nuclear missiles. Civ V has an array of difficulties for different play styles, and one of them is sure to suit you. Almost every time I play this game (multiplayer) , I end up getting completely and utterly destroyed, but I would not trade it for the world. Pros: Giant Death Robots Multiple Victories Many different civilizations to play Near-seamless multiplayer Destroying enemy cities Naming your cities hilarious things Researching techs in your order Overall exciting experiences Variation of difficulties Cons: Ghandi is the ultimate war machine and he will not stop until your empire has been reduced the ash and a handful of starving citizens suffering from radiation and burns. If you see Ghandi in your civ game, it's time to wave the white flag. Haha. 11/10 Would Recommend
